      "APPEAL_NO": "SC.195/2010",
      "JURISDICTION_ISSUE": "CONTRACT – PRELIMINARY NEGOTIATION – Whether sufficient to establish the existence of a Contract or determine which court has jurisdiction JURISDICTION – TERRITORIAL JURISDICTION – FCT High Court vis a vis Rivers State High Court – How determined – Whether FCT High Court is vested with jurisdiction when parties involved are resident in and the contract is to be executed Rivers State",
      "FACTS": "The Appellant entered into a contract of supply with the 1st Respondent under which she was to supply 4 Cruise Boats. According to paragraph 8 of the Appellant’s claim, \"most of the negotiations of the contract\" between the parties took place in Abuja. Eventually, negotiations were concluded and the contract came into being. The Appellant supplied the Boats. Having executed the contract he made several demands for payment. The Respondents eventually paid the sum of N9,853,610.90 as part-payment. The Appellant issued a Writ of Summons in the Federal Capital Territory High Court, Abuja, under the Undefended List Procedure claiming the balance of the debt. The Respondents despite being served with processes declined entering any appearance nor filing any Notice of Intention to defend as enjoined by the Rules of the trial Court. In the absence of a Notice of Intention to defend, the trial Court was urged to invoke the provisions of Order 21 Rule 4 of the FCT High Court and to enter judgment for the Appellant. Judgment was accordingly entered for her as per the claims under the Undefended List. The Respondents appealed to the Court of Appeal, contending that the trial Court had no jurisdiction to entertain the suit as the parties involved were resident in, the contract entered into and executed in Port Harcourt, Rivers State. The appellate Court allowed the appeal holding that under Order 9, Rule 3 of the FCT High Court Rules, actions for breach of contract should be commenced where the contract ought to have been performed or where the Defendant resided. It further held that under the Section 255 of the Constitution of the Federal Republic of Nigeria which created the FCT High Court the Court has no jurisdiction as the matter has nothing to do with Abuja, FCT, but Port Harcourt, Rivers State. The Court, accordingly dismissed the suit. The Appellant has appealed to the Supreme Court",
      "ISSUES_FOR_DETERMINATION": [
        "Whether the High Court of the Federal Capital Territory Abuja, has jurisdiction to entertain a suit bordering on contract, where the parties to the contract reside in Port Harcourt and the contract entered and to be executed in Port Harcourt."
      ],
      "HELD": "1. that negotiation is at best a prelude to reaching an agreement; 2. that there may well be negotiation which does not germinate into a contract or agreement as a result of the inability to reach a compromise; 3. that territorial jurisdiction refers to the power or authority of a Court to adjudicate over matters which occur or arise within a territory or geographical area; 4. that the FCT is the territorial limit within which the trial FCT High Court is guaranteed in the exercise of the constitutional and other statutory jurisdiction vested or conferred on it. 5. that territorial jurisdiction implies a geographical area within which the authority of the Court may be exercised and outside which the Court has no power to act; 6. that in cases of breach of contract, the territorial jurisdiction to hear the case can be determined by reference to the following: (a) where the contract was made (lex loci contractus); (b) where the contract is to be performed (lex loci solutions); (c) where the defendant resides; 7. that Order 9 Rule 3 envisages that the contract must have been performed within the Federal Capital Territory to clothe the High Court with jurisdiction to determine the suit; 8. that a Court must not only have subject matter jurisdiction but also territorial jurisdiction to competently and properly adjudicate on any dispute brought before it; Obiter That there is no justification for the institution of the suit before the High Court of the FCT in Abuja, the filing of the such suit before that Court is a clear example of \"forum shopping\" in the hope of securing a favorable outcome, that practice has been seriously deprecated as it does not augur well for the administration of justice Appeal Dismissed",
